OL,6,FHowever, the prosecution had argued
OL,7,Fthat '"common sense" should have been
OL,8,Fused when they were aware that Mr
OL,9,FRogers was under the water for more
OL,10,Fthan five minutes.
OL,12,FAll three defendants previously said
OL,13,Fthat they were never trained in what
OL,14,Fto do if someone was suffering an
OL,15,Fhypoxic blackout, the loss of
OL,16,Fconsciousness in shallow water due to
OL,17,Fa lack of oxygen, and that they were
OL,18,Faware of Christopher Rogers and were
OL,19,Fwatching him.
